<font color="#FF0000">CETAN &amp; EYAH IN THE JUNGLE RVN</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 21 16:26:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
EYAH was an Army Brat. In the Corps we had someone similiar to that but we called him the D.I. <br>
But if you show me where Eyah's at, I still have a hundred round belt of tracers and I'll gladly carve out his heart for you with the sixty. <br><br>
I once met Eyah face to face. He at first looked like a beautiful harmless little dark green colored leech. Leeches are suppose to take the bad blood out a Vietnamese villager had once told us but by the time I found out this one was not a leech but an Eyah he had grown to ten times his size and had sucked a pint of blood right out of me.<br>
 <br>
We cut off his head (twice, on account we didn't know which end was up), we then tied the rest of him to a M-79 round. Figured that would teach him and his cousins a lesson, so that they would leave us alone. <br>
I now know that's why those hooches in Nam had those little altars right inside the front door to keep little leeches, Eyah's and the communist away. <br><br>
Another time on operation Knox we ran into a whole bunch of them, they had turned themselves into rock apes. All night long they kept throwing rocks and tree branches at us and making all kinds of noise and that either scared you to death, or made you pee in your pants. Do Eyah's smell bad? Because those sure did. But that reminds me of the gook we captured poor guy was so scared of going on the chopper that he peed all over himself and lost all his bowels on the chopper. Sure glad I did not have to clean that one.<br><br>
We're all scared of things we don't understand, to me it was easier to have just opened up with a twenty round burst and the rock apes would have gone away. Then Charlie would have known where we were. It was safer to tolerate the smell when Eyah went by because we could not tell if he was pretending to be a rock ape or really was Charlie in disguise. The smell seemed to be about the same. But who then was the real enemy?  <br>
The rock apes just wanted us to leave, the enemy was looking for us, and all we wanted to do was to get good nights sleep. I guess it would have been easier to have opened up, but then the rock apes I know would have turned themselves into gooks and they would have shot back with little and big guns and because of the smell I wouldn't have been able to tell which was which, but then again neither could they. Perhaps to them we were Eyah.<br>

<p><code>-- cookbarela@iname.com  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


